What the Post Is About
The post is sharing a new theoretical physics paper with the title:
“How traversable is a traversable wormhole?”
Authors: Ben Freivogel, Alessandro Fumagalli, Marija Tomašević
arXiv: 2606.12528 [hep-th, gr-qc]
This is a mainstream high-energy physics / general relativity paper that examines the practical difficulties and limitations of making a wormhole traversable.
Simple Explanation
In standard general relativity, a traversable wormhole (one that could theoretically be crossed) usually requires exotic matter with negative energy density to keep the throat open. Even if you have that exotic matter, there are still major problems:
Stability issues
The amount of negative energy required
How long the wormhole can stay open
Whether anything (or anyone) can actually pass through without being destroyed
This paper is likely analyzing how realistic or impractical traversable wormholes are under current theoretical understanding — basically asking: “Even if we assume we can create one, how actually traversable would it be in practice?”
